Pre-Game Insights: Defending champions England started their World Cup campaign with a rain-affected match against Scotland.
England are fourth in Group B with one point, while Australia are second with two points after beating Oman in their opener.
A defeat to ODI world champions Australia on Saturday could leave England’s Super Eight qualification in jeopardy.
Jonny Bairstow emphasized the importance of winning more games than losing in tournament cricket.
Bairstow described the contest between the Ashes rivals as 'a great spectacle'.
Australia had a shaky start in their match against Oman before all-rounder Marcus Stoinis shone with the bat and ball.
Captain Mitchell Marsh said his side felt a bit nervous in their game against Oman but were happy with the win and looking forward to the clash with England.
Marsh expects England fans to outnumber the Australians for the match at Barbados.
Australia started their campaign with a win over Oman and had a successful series against New Zealand and the West Indies before the tournament.
England’s first World Cup match with Scotland ended in no result after rain wrecked the contest.
Kensington Oval has hosted four matches with varied results, and rain is forecast around the match time.
Miscellaneous Highlights: Australia and England have played 23 T20 internationals, with England winning 11 games, Australia 10 and two contests ending in no result.
Pat Cummins will return for this match after being rested against Oman.
Mitchell Starc, who left the field in the last game with cramp, is expected to be fit.
England do not have any injury concerns.
